<br>
If you are given a way to ensure, or as sure as we have it with stuns, that you keep aggro through the initial few seconds of combat, given the other (though slight) advantages you have, why would most groups want to have a knight?  We do get extras (heals, interrupts, stuns or taps and dots) but give up quite a bit of one to do the other. <br>
<br>
I'm not sure if I know the best way to balance it where it would be more of a tossup for which was preferred, but I do think that going straight aggro manipulation is not the way to go about it.  The problem with this is that the issue lies nearly 100% with straight aggro generation. <br>
<br>
I do most of my grouping within my guild, and always see warriors getting tank spots and not having a problem. It could be because we know how to work with each other giving an advantage over normal pickup groups, but in many cases I do not see the issue as being that great.  <br>
<br>
I know there are problems on both sides seeing the exact reasons the others have, and I know I don't want warriors to be useless, but I dont really want to be back to 2nd choice tank when its the only role I fill, and I can imagine you do not as well. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dwelfnvhal>DwelfnVhal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 64<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/22/03 6:57:44 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: lol</span><hr size=1> All I can say is that currently I can tank or I can do nothing of major use. <br>
<br>
Paladins and SK's can and do get groups for what their other abilities offer to a non-optimal group - wether that's enough of a balance or not I can't say...but in the absense of a warrior Knights are now a perfectly acceptable alternative anyway. The reverse is not true. If a group has a main tank of any sort there is virtually no reason to add a warrior because he provides nothing 'extra' in a noticeable sense.<br>
<br>
Now here's the slightly wierd sounding bit. The role of the tank is NOT truely to be the very best at damage mitigation, his primary purpose (so long as he can survive with some amount of efficiency) is to ensure that the mob is hitting one target - himself. As such in a non-specialised situation, aggro control is far more important than mitigation. If we accept that fact then any change to make a warrior more acceptable in his old role has to deal with the aggro issue as it currently stands.<br>
<br>
The warrior has always been a class specialised around the one major role of 'THE TANK'. For this pre-eminence he pays a very high price (no spells, no means to travel faster than runspeed, no way to control adds, no 'get out of jail free' cards, near utter dependance on a group of other people to do ANYTHING worthy of note...) as things stand at the moment he has no major advantage in mitigation (outside of small peaks about 4-5 times an hour) over a knight and far less ability to control the aggro situation - no matter how well timed his taunts, how great the aggro on his weapons (not much use if the skill check fails or they don't proc).<br>
<br>
Whilst i can fully understand your wish to be wanted in groups, can you honestly say that it's fair for a class solely specialised around one function to be on the brink of marginalisation in that function?<br>
<br>
Warriors still get groups yes, but it's my contention that that is now based mostly on perceptions dating back to kunark etc. On anything but exceptional mobs a Knight fulfills the main tank role perfectly adequately. This whole thread was started by someone complaining at the way more and more people are recognising that fact and choosing knights over warriors leaving him with no role.<br>
<br>
Don't underestimate the impact that seeing this inability to do our job 'properly' has on us warriors either. Knowing that at some point in your exp session the RNG is gonna bite you doesn't increase ones enthusiasm, if the problem occurs at the wrong moment it may well cause a lot of disruption or even a TPW. Certainly playing with experienced friends minimises that possibility but it remains far more likely with warrior aggro.<br>
<br>
In the past, whilst that possibility remained frustratingly likely, it was a clear and neccessary trade off to have a tank that could take the beating - no longer is there that justification.<br>
<br>
Either the warriors role needs to be redefined in an exp situation or something has to change - unfortunately I don't see how warriors mitigation can be increased without totally unbalancing every encounter currently in game - to me that leaves aggro control as the simplest route to parity.<br>
<br>
